Greentown China, HSBC, Swire Pacific: Hong Kong Equities Preview

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-09-23T00:42:52Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-23/greentown-china-hsbc-swire-pacific-hong-kong-equities-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  slumped 4.9 percent to 17,911.95. The
Hang Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H
shares of Chinese companies, tumbled 6.3 percent to 9,202.70.  Alibaba.com Ltd. (1688)  (1688 HK): DST Global and Silver Lake
agreed to invest as much as $1.6 billion in Alibaba Group
Holding Ltd., the parent of Alibaba.com., in a transaction
valuing the company at $32 billion, said two people familiar
with the deal. Alibaba.com, operator of China’s biggest online
commerce site for business owners, declined 5 percent to HK$6.80.  Greentown China Holdings Ltd. (3900)  (3900 HK): The largest
builder in the eastern province of Zhejiang said it has no
trouble financing its loans and denied a Reuters report it’s
being investigated by the nation’s banking regulator. Greentown
slumped 16 percent to HK$4.49 after Reuters reported that
China’s banking regulator told  trust companies  to report
dealings with the developer.  HSBC Holdings Plc (HSBA)  (5 HK): Europe’s largest lender by market
value may report lower revenue for the second half of the year
than previously estimated, analysts at Espirito Santo Investment
Bank said after a meeting with Finance Director Iain Mackay.
“This looks like a top-line downgrade to us for HSBC, but for
the wider European banking sector there are major concerns about
funding,” the analysts, led by Joseph Dickerson, wrote in a
note to clients yesterday. HSBC sank 3.6 percent to HK$60.65.  Huadian Power International Corp. (1071 HK): The
electricity producer in China said it agreed to buy two
companies involved in hydropower for 1.69 billion yuan ($217
million). The stock slumped 5 percent to HK$1.15.  Swire Pacific Ltd. (19)  (19 HK): The commercial landlord and
owner of Hong Kong’s biggest airline said it’s considering a
spin off and separate listing of Swire Properties Ltd. in Hong
Kong, a year after the real-estate company shelved an initial
share sale. Swire plans to distribute a 17 stake in the unit to
public shareholders of the listed company and controlling
shareholder John Swire & Sons Ltd., it said. Swire dropped 3.7
percent to HK$91.55.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan Burgos in Singapore at 
 jburgos4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle in  Tokyo  at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 